def: Trickery; also, a trick. [Obs.] Rom. of R.
Applied to a line which is the sum of two lines commensurableonly in power (as the side and diagonal of a square).
Tending to exaggerate; involving exaggeration. "Exaggerativelanguage." Geddes. "Exaggerative pictures." W. J. Linton.-- Ex*ag"ger*a*tive*ly, adv. Carlyle.
An image or effigy; -- used rather in an abstract sense, andrarely for a work of art.
A wether sheep between one and two years old. [Scot.]
To adorn. [Obs.]Congealed little drops which do the morn adore. Spenser.
Making void; rendering null; as, a frustratory appeal. [Obs.]Ayliffe.
To walk; to move about. [R.] Southey.
